{"id":"project-LICHEN-hpyz","title":"SLIP transport: ESC in IDLE state doesn't reset rx buffers","description":"File: lichen/subsys/lichen/transport/slip_transport.c
Lines: 220-222

When in SLIP_STATE_IDLE and receiving an ESC byte, the state transitions to SLIP_STATE_ESC but rx_len and rx_overflow are not reset:

    case SLIP_STATE_IDLE:
        if (b == SLIP_END) {
            /* Empty frame or frame delimiter - stay idle */
            ctx->rx_len = 0;
            ctx->rx_overflow = false;
        } else if (b == SLIP_ESC) {
            ctx->rx_state = SLIP_STATE_ESC;  // rx_len not reset!
        } else {
            /* First data byte */
            ctx->rx_state = SLIP_STATE_DATA;
            ctx->rx_len = 0;
            ctx->rx_overflow = false;
            ...
        }

If stale data exists in rx_pkt from a previous aborted frame, it could affect the new frame if rx_len is non-zero.

The regular data byte case properly resets rx_len to 0, but the ESC case doesn't. While subsequent DATA state handling appends, starting from a non-zero rx_len would corrupt the frame.

